Perfect. Now I have all the information I need. Let me create a comprehensive analysis document:

## Routine Duplication Bug Analysis

I've traced the complete Hevy routine creation flow during setup. Here's the full picture of the duplication issue:

### The Core Problem

When a user re-runs setup after a DB reset, new routines are created in Hevy instead of reusing existing ones. The issue: **the routine duplication detection relies on `routine_mappings` table, which was just reset** — it has no memory of previously created Hevy routines.

### Complete Code Path Trace

#### 1. **handleSetup** (`/Users/ryanr/Code/hevy-planner/src/index.ts`, lines 560-600)

This is where routine creation happens. The logic flow:

**Lines 561-565: Load existing mappings**
```
const allMappings = await getExerciseTemplateMappings(env.DB, userId);
const existingRoutineMappings = await getRoutineMappings(env.DB, userId);
const existingMap = new Map(
  existingRoutineMappings.map((m) => [m.program_routine_id, m.hevy_routine_id])
);
```

After a DB reset, `existingRoutineMappings` is an empty array, so `existingMap` is empty.

**Lines 567-570: Folder creation decision**
```
const hasNewRoutines = program.routines.some((r) => !existingMap.has(r.id));
const folder = hasNewRoutines
  ? await client.getOrCreateRoutineFolder(program.meta.title)
  : null;
```

Since `existingMap` is empty, `hasNewRoutines` is **always true**, and a folder is created/fetched. But here's the key: `getOrCreateRoutineFolder` is idempotent—it checks if a folder with the program title exists and reuses it.

**Lines 572-591: Routine creation loop**
```
for (const routine of program.routines) {
  const payload = buildRoutinePayload(routine, allMappings);
  const existingHevyId = existingMap.get(routine.id);  // Always null after DB reset

  if (existingHevyId) {
    // Update path — never taken on re-setup
    await client.updateRoutine(existingHevyId, {...});
    routineIdMap.set(routine.id, existingHevyId);
  } else {
    // Create path — always taken on re-setup
    if (!folder) throw new Error(...);
    const created = await client.createRoutine({
      title: payload.title,
      folder_id: folder.id,
      exercises: payload.exercises,
    });
    routineIdMap.set(routine.id, created.id);
  }
}
```

The problem: **existingHevyId is always null** because `existingMap` is empty. So it always takes the `else` branch and calls `client.createRoutine()`, even though the routine may already exist in Hevy with the same name in the same folder.

**Lines 594-600: Save mappings**
```
for (const [programRoutineId, hevyRoutineId] of routineIdMap) {
  await upsertRoutineMapping(env.DB, {
    user_id: userId,
    program_routine_id: programRoutineId,
    hevy_routine_id: hevyRoutineId,
  });
}
```

New mappings are upserted, but only for the newly created routines. Previous routines have no mapping.

---

#### 2. **getOrCreateRoutineFolder** (`/Users/ryanr/Code/hevy-planner/src/hevy/client.ts`, lines 126-131)

```typescript
async getOrCreateRoutineFolder(name: string): Promise<{ id: number; title: string }> {
  const folders = await this.getRoutineFolders();
  const existing = folders.find((f) => f.title === name);
  if (existing) return existing;
  return this.createRoutineFolder(name);
}
```

This is **correctly idempotent**. It finds the folder by name and reuses it. The folder check works; the routine check does not.

**Related methods:**
- `getRoutineFolders()` (lines 103-115): Paginates through all routine folders
- `createRoutineFolder()` (lines 117-124): Creates a new folder, returns `{ id, title }`

---

#### 3. **getRoutineMappings and upsertRoutineMapping** (`/Users/ryanr/Code/hevy-planner/src/storage/queries.ts`, lines 112-136)

**getRoutineMappings (lines 112-121):**
```typescript
export async function getRoutineMappings(
  db: D1Database,
  userId: string
): Promise<RoutineMappingRow[]> {
  const result = await db
    .prepare("SELECT * FROM routine_mappings WHERE user_id = ?")
    .bind(userId)
    .all<RoutineMappingRow>();
  return result.results;
}
```

On DB reset, this returns `[]` because the `routine_mappings` table is empty.

**upsertRoutineMapping (lines 123-136):**
```typescript
export async function upsertRoutineMapping(
  db: D1Database,
  mapping: RoutineMappingRow
): Promise<void> {
  await db
    .prepare(
      `INSERT INTO routine_mappings (user_id, program_routine_id, hevy_routine_id)
       VALUES (?, ?, ?)
       ON CONFLICT(user_id, program_routine_id) DO UPDATE SET
         hevy_routine_id = excluded.hevy_routine_id`
    )
    .bind(mapping.user_id, mapping.program_routine_id, mapping.hevy_routine_id)
    .run();
}
```

This correctly uses `ON CONFLICT` for idempotency. But it only saves the **newly created** routines from `routineIdMap` (which is built in the setup handler).

---

#### 4. **bulkSetQueueItemRoutineIds** (`/Users/ryanr/Code/hevy-planner/src/storage/queries.ts`, lines 138-151)

```typescript
export async function bulkSetQueueItemRoutineIds(
  db: D1Database,
  userId: string,
  routineIdMap: Map<string, string>
): Promise<void> {
  if (routineIdMap.size === 0) return;
  const stmt = db.prepare(
    "UPDATE queue_items SET hevy_routine_id = ? WHERE user_id = ? AND routine_id = ?"
  );
  const batch = [...routineIdMap.entries()].map(([programRoutineId, hevyRoutineId]) =>
    stmt.bind(hevyRoutineId, userId, programRoutineId)
  );
  await db.batch(batch);
}
```

This updates all queue items with the `hevy_routine_id` from `routineIdMap`. On re-setup, `routineIdMap` only contains newly created routines, so old queue items won't get updated with duplicate routine IDs (which is good), but new queue items will be created with references to the new duplicates.

---

#### 5. **generatePlaylist** (`/Users/ryanr/Code/hevy-planner/src/domain/queue.ts`, lines 8-37)

```typescript
export function generatePlaylist(
  template: WeekTemplate,
  routines: Routine[],
  weeks: number
): PlaylistItem[] {
  const routineMap = new Map(routines.map((r) => [r.id, r]));
  const mainRoutineOrder: string[] = [];

  for (const day of template.days) {
    if (!day.routineIDs) continue;
    for (const rid of day.routineIDs) {
      const routine = routineMap.get(rid);
      if (routine && !routine.isDaily) {
        mainRoutineOrder.push(rid);
      }
    }
  }

  const playlist: PlaylistItem[] = [];
  for (let week = 0; week < weeks; week++) {
    for (const rid of mainRoutineOrder) {
      playlist.push({
        routine_id: rid,
        position: playlist.length,
      });
    }
  }

  return playlist;
}
```

This function generates queue items with `routine_id` (program routine ID), not Hevy IDs. It does **not** detect duplicates—it simply repeats the template for N weeks. On re-setup, new queue items are generated with the same `program` routine IDs.

---

### Schema Context

**routine_mappings table** (`/Users/ryanr/Code/hevy-planner/migrations/0001_initial.sql`, lines 39-44):
```sql
CREATE TABLE routine_mappings (
  user_id TEXT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id),
  program_routine_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  hevy_routine_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (user_id, program_routine_id)
);
```

Composite primary key on `(user_id, program_routine_id)`, ensuring at most one mapping per program routine per user. This is the only way to detect existing Hevy routines on re-setup.

---

### Why Duplication Happens

